==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{m|enm|forsaken||to reject, deny}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{m|ang|forsacan||to dispute, quarrel, refuse, oppose}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{m|gem-pro|*frasakaną||to renounce}}, equivalent to {{prefix|for|sake|lang=en}}. Akin to West Frisian {{m|fy|fersaakje}}, {{cog|nl|verzaken||to renounce; forsake}}, {{cog|gmh|versachen||to deny}}, {{cog|da|forsage||to give up}}, {{cog|no|forsake||to give up, renounce}}, {{cog|sv|försaka||to give up, to be without}}, {{cog|got|𐍃𐌰𐌺𐌰𐌽||to rebuke, quarrel}}.<ref>{{R:Webster 1913|forsake}}</ref>

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|/fɔɹˈseɪk/|lang=en}}
* {{rhymes|eɪk|lang=en}}

===Verb===
{{en-verb|forsakes|forsaking|forsook|forsaken}}

# To [[abandon]], to give up, to [[leave]] ''([[permanently]])'', to [[renounce]].
#* '''1911''': {{w|Ameen Rihani}}, {{w|The Book of Khalid}}, p.39
#*: There may be nothing noble in renouncing one's country, in abandoning one's home, in '''forsaking''' one's people; but is there not something remarkable in this great move one makes.
#* '''1998''', "{{w|Damien (South Park)|Damien}}", season 1, episode 10 of ''{{w|South Park}}''
#*: Stan: You've got to fight, Jesus.
#*: Jesus: Why, what's the point? No one believes in me. Everyone put their money on Satan. My father '''forsaked'''{{sic}} me, the town '''forsaked'''{{sic}} me. I'm completely '''forsook'''{{sic}}.

